The bee car that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for the prevention of accidents Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Brand Management Technology and Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an expansion of the Security Shield from four areas of Nissan.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capacity of the brand's vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that looks very much like the Nissan Security Shield.
But the most important thing is the composite eyes of the bee, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, which allows you to fly without interruption within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles that are up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to a microprocessor on board which, immediately, results in the prevention of collision.
"At the time you detect an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a straight or higher angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, for the small robot to avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can function continuously with only a couple of dozen KB memory.
This may be surprising, but we're not talking about memory gigas, not even mega."
This is the first step to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan vaticin will introduce into serial cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
