Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around the socialism of the twenty-first century.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he is the third one to vote on a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results referring to 80% of the vote.
According to these results, "no" achieved 28 %, 7 % of the votes cast were null and 0,7 % were blank.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the start of the electoral centres and a count from a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory to "yes", estimated at between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on Sunday night to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The " Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly " had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians leading the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Michaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will be held in full calm, according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the " new socialism " advocated by the President.
The draft Constitution implies an increase in the power of the State over the economy, reserving it the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and through foreign currency sent by its emigrants.
Under the leadership of Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives strengthened powers to the Head of State, who can make up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it would use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of the free provision of health and education services which the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provided for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which would put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 abducted persons have been released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good when they arrived at 1530 hours on board a special aircraft at the military base of Al Maza, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Some helicopters immediately transported them to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They find themselves in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana at the airport.
On 19 September, these hostages fell into the possession of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying a safari in all-terrain in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then they have moved from one zulo to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of the safari organization.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 members of the special forces, carried on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
" An exchange of shots took place, and they killed half the kidnappers, the others have fled, " said this official who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "light" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commanders.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve of the day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrain aboard which were the kidnappers, of whom six were killed, including the Chadian chief and two were arrested.
He also stated that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a statement immediately denied by this group.
