The European Union doubles its trade with India
Since the European Union and India are reciprocally trading partners, this issue in addition to the other problems largely global dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
While the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not addressed at the ninth summit in Marseille yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso President of the Commission and Javier Solana Senior Representative of Foreign Policy, received Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, that is to say to increase their trade to more than 100 billion euros.
In view of the fact that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
This brought the twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India into line with the law, and air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade treaty with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth largest trading partner in the Union.
The summit paid its attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of terrorism - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also urged, although both sides have a great responsibility for their failure.
The EU confirmed that it will hold on to its energy and climate programme, i.e. by 2020 it wants to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20 percent.
India also agrees with this, as at the climate conference next year, a global agreement should be reached and the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 per cent by 2050.
They also wished to impede the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris trusts that French companies will be charged EUR 20 billion to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
