Found Steve Fossett's plane the missing millionaire a year ago
the remains of Steve Fossett's plane, the millionaire disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The debris has been found on an altiplane at 3000 metres above sea level, in the Nevada mountain range of Mammoth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
The Commissioner of Madeira County, John Anderson, has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squad, and now we have the confirmation that it is the very thing that Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance," he said at a print conference.
The Commissioner has specified that no human remains have been found on or around the plane.
The 63-year-old millionaire was killed in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Office (Ntsb) has reported that a few hours after the sighting of the remains, a team of investigators has been sent that has identified the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from Nevada's trust, some personal remains of Fossett have been found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents named Fossett, the two issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been interrupted one month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a position in history thanks to a long series of primordials.
In 2002, at the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the world's turn into an aerostatic balloon: two lonely weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the world's turn by plane and without ladders.
Among his records, also that for flying at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a copilot.
